<subSubSection id="E08F6519FFF8FF87A18062E7CD55FEDF" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="174" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A82A3692FFF8FF87A18062E7CD55FEDF" blockId="2.[151,1437,1601,2024]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,151,321]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="174" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis id="9AE1EA80FFF8FF86A18062E7CF0CF88E" bold="true" box="[199,315,1782,1808]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Remarks.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="772E8830FFF8FF86A03662E7CFE4F88E" box="[369,467,1782,1808]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">holotype</typeStatus>
female (
<figureCitation id="30AE2A17FFF8FF86A37562E7CC43F88E" box="[562,628,1782,1808]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1285,1309]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,567,1242]" captionTargetId="figure-199@2.[151,1436,561,1261]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Syntype female of Cephennium breviusculum Motschulsky (1); aedeagus of Cephennodes zwaluwenburgi Zim- merman in ventral (2) and lateral (3) views; holotype female of Cephennium felicitas Scott (4)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5069658" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5069658/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) is tiny (body length 
<quantity id="6F6D9B77FFF8FF86A21B62E7CD88F88E" box="[860,959,1782,1808]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.8" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" unit="mm" value="0.78">0.78 mm</quantity>
) and stout (elytral index 1.13). The internal prothoracic ‘cavities’ are clearly visible as translucent spots near each hind pronotal corner, and the prosternal process is strongly elevated, both features clearly indicating that this species does not belong in 
<taxonomicName id="6F954D11FFF8FF86A5A9632FCB4BF8C6" box="[1262,1404,1854,1880]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Cephennium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9AE1EA80FFF8FF86A5A9632FCB4BF8C6" box="[1262,1404,1854,1880]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Cephennium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="6F954D11FFF8FF86A1D06373CF9AF8E2" authority="Reitter" authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1907" box="[151,429,1890,1916]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Cephennomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9AE1EA80FFF8FF86A1D06373CF62F8E2" box="[151,341,1890,1916]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Cephennomicrus</emphasis>
Reitter
</taxonomicName>
, but in 
<taxonomicName id="6F954D11FFF8FF86A34F6373CDA1F8E2" box="[520,918,1890,1916]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pomphopsilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="9AE1EA80FFF8FF86A34F6373CC93F8E2" box="[520,676,1890,1916]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Pomphopsilla</emphasis>
Jałoszyński. Species
</taxonomicName>
of 
<taxonomicName id="6F954D11FFF8FF86A2866373CA6AF8E2" box="[961,1117,1890,1916]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pomphopsilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9AE1EA80FFF8FF86A2866373CA6AF8E2" box="[961,1117,1890,1916]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Pomphopsilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are primarily diagnosed by the male genitalia, and identifications of females are difficult and possible only when they have been collected together with males from the same spot. However, 
<taxonomicName id="6F954D11FFF8FF86A38C63BACD09F85A" authorityName="Scott" authorityYear="1922" box="[715,830,1962,1988]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Cephennium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="felicitas">
<emphasis id="9AE1EA80FFF8FF86A38C63BACD09F85A" box="[715,830,1962,1988]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">P. felicitas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is remarkable and unique in having extremely shallow antebasal pronotal pits, especially the outer pair is barely discernible. The inner pair is not connected by a transverse groove, unlike in 
<taxonomicName id="6F954D11FFF9FF87A0256486CC45FF2F" authority="(Scott, 1922)" baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1922" box="[354,626,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pomphopsilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crenata">
<emphasis id="9AE1EA80FFF9FF87A0256486CFE3FF2E" box="[354,468,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">P. crenata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="CC044B63FFF9FF87A0A36486CC5DFF2F" author="Scott, H." box="[484,618,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" pagination="195 - 260" refId="ref3155" refString="Scott, H. (1922) No. IV. - Coleoptera: Scydmaenidae, Scaphidiidae, Phalacridae, Cucujidae (Supplement), Lathridiidae, Mycetophagidae (including Propalticus), Bostrychidae, Lyctidae. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, Serie 2, Zoology, 18 (1), 195 - 260. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1922. tb 00550. x" type="journal article" year="1922">Scott, 1922</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the other congener known to occur in 
<collectingCountry id="D0827602FFF9FF87A5736486CA9BFF2F" box="[1076,1196,151,177]" name="Seychelles" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
(but on the island of 
<collectingCountry id="D0827602FFF9FF87A1D064AACEEBFF48" box="[151,220,187,214]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Mahé</collectingCountry>
). The shallow and barely discernible pits are presumably the reason why 
<bibRefCitation id="CC044B63FFF9FF87A55E64AACA92FF4B" author="Scott, H." box="[1049,1189,187,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" pagination="195 - 260" refId="ref3155" refString="Scott, H. (1922) No. IV. - Coleoptera: Scydmaenidae, Scaphidiidae, Phalacridae, Cucujidae (Supplement), Lathridiidae, Mycetophagidae (including Propalticus), Bostrychidae, Lyctidae. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, Serie 2, Zoology, 18 (1), 195 - 260. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1922. tb 00550. x" type="journal article" year="1922">Scott (1922)</bibRefCitation>
placed this species in 
<taxonomicName id="6F954D11FFF9FF87A1D064CECF12FF67" box="[151,293,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Cephennium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9AE1EA80FFF9FF87A1D064CECF12FF67" box="[151,293,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Cephennium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, despite being much more similar to all remaining 
<taxonomicName id="6F954D11FFF9FF87A23464CECDCBFF67" authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1882" box="[883,1020,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Cephenniini">Cephenniini</taxonomicName>
described by him based on material from the Percy Sladen Trust Expedition, which he placed in 
